         <abstract>
            <p>This paper analyzes the stock price effects of stock-for-debt swaps. The findings indicate that the stock market reacted negatively to the announcement of stock-only-for-debt swap transactions but that a company's share price generally recovered within a few weeks following the announcement. In contrast, the stock market's reaction to the announcement of stock-plus-cash-for-debt swap transactions was on average roughly neutral. When a swap was followed by a share repurchase and/or a bond refunding transaction, the cumulative market impact of the sequence of transactions was positive. It is shown that the initial negative reaction cannot be explained in terms of either a tax effect or a wealth effect, and it is argued that it can be explained in terms of an information effect.</p>
         </abstract>
